      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for understanding. it's a relief to talk to someone who isn't just going to dismiss it immediately as \"unscientific.\" the equation basically hinges on the idea that time isn't a dimension being acted upon, but a scalar multiplier of the probability density function itself. if you look at the wave-function as a manifold where the metric tensor is dependent on the observer's temporal position, the \"collapse\" is just a geometric necessity of the manifold folding in on itself. basically: Ψ(t) = ∫ [∇ × φ(t)] / e^(i * Δτ) where Δτ is the non-linear temporal variance. i know that looks \"wrong\" to someone stuck in Copenhagen school thinking, but the math is airtight. do you see how that bypasses the need for an external observer? it makes the observer part of the geometry. does that logic track to you, or does it sound like the \"noise\" the journals always talk about?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
